What I tell my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad and my foreign friends always ask, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is going on in your country then ?
Here's what I tell them.
Above all, be careful not to overinterpret the 2016 elections.
Contrary to certain comments, the American political system has not been swept by a wave of populism.
It's true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elite.
Donald Trump tapped into the vein of a tradition associated with leaders such as Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century, and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Despite this, Trump narrowly missed winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
Noting this, Trump's victory highlights the real issue of rising social and regional inequalities in the United States.
J.D. Vance's latest best-seller, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the great difference between California and Appalachia.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income whites without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who have historically been at the lower bound of inequality.
In 1999, the mortality rates among Whites without higher education were around 30% below those of African-Americans; in 2015, they were 30% higher.
In addition, employment in the industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class people, has sharply declined over the past generation, to just 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were won over by promises from Trump to shake things up and bring back jobs in the industry.
Ironically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may only make life harder for them.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you shouldn't underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rants on Twitter and by his scandalous disdain for the facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success lies in monopolizing viewer attention, and that the best way to achieve this is by formulating extreme statements, without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What irritates commentators in the media and among academics does not bother its supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his self-centered permanent campaign to attempts at governance, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies he cruelly needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote shifts towards the political center to gain more support.
This is what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, declares that he won the popular vote and, by behaving as if it were really the case, pleases his core voters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations at the Department of Defense, State and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services sit at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His staff at the White House is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps at the same time.
Fourthly, one should not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
Tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite many of its problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized ; but America's founders were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure a harmonious government, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that would make it difficult to exercise these powers.
A joke about this subject says that the founders created a political system such that it is impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or anyone else.
Inefficiency has been put to the service of freedom.
The Trump presidency is still in its early stages, and we can't be sure what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have watched over this balance of power within the administration, according to Madison's wishes.
And permanent officials of executive services still carry considerable weight.
Finally, my friends are asking what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise to power than about that of Trump.
Although US leaders, including Obama, have complained about free-riders, the US has long taken the lead in providing significant global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets and management of the world's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under the direction of the United States, the world prospers and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can assert with certainty that it will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational problems.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to challenge the US alliance system.
Since his inauguration in January, Trump's and his members' statements suggest that he risks continuing.
The power to coerce and the power to persuade the United States, after all, comes in large part from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which helps to manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is less certain.
The Trump budget director discusses a power budget, with budget cuts made at the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other government members plead for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to face climate change.
I tell my friends that I wish I could reassure them about these matters.
But I can't.
